gramas y Videogramas|AMPROFON]])<ref name=\"mex2019\">{{cite web|url=http://amprofon.com.mx/es/pages/rankings/top-album.php |title=Top 100 M\u00e9xico - Los m\u00e1s vendidos 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2020|language=Spanish |publisher=Asociaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas |archive-url=http://archive.is/2Q5LT|archive-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref> \n| 1\n|-\n{{album chart|New Zealand|2|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Norway|3|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Poland|3|id=1226|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Portugal|1|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 28, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Scotland|1|date=20190816|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Spain|1|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Sweden|4|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|2|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK2|1|date=20190816|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 17, 2019|refname=OCC}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"BB200\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rolling Stone Top 200|''Rolling Stone'' Top 200]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/charts/albums/2019-08-09/|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| 1\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Albums (ARIA)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariacharts.com.au/annual-charts/2019/albums-chart|title=ARIA End of Year Albums Chart 2019|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| 49\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Austrian Albums (\u00d63 Austria)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://austriancharts.at/year.asp?cat=a&id=2019|title=Jahreshitparade Alben 2019|website=austriancharts.at|accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| 55\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Belgian Albums (Ultratop Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=2019&cat=a|title=Jaaroverzichten 2019|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| 73\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Belgian Albums (Ultratop Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2019&cat=a|title=Rapports Annuels 2019|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| 146\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| French Albums (SNEP)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-lannee/top-albums-annee/?annee=2019|title=Top de l'ann\u00e9e Top Albums 2019|publisher=SNEP|language=fr|access-date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 187\n|- \n! scope=\"row\"| Mexican Albums (AMPROFON)<ref name=\"mex2019\"/>\n| 94\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Swiss Albums (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/charts/jahreshitparade/2019|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 2019|website=hitparade.ch|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| 66\n|}\n\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=album|artist=Slipknot|title=We Are Not Your Kind|award=Silver|salesamount=60,000}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{discogs master|1586847}}\n\n{{Slipknot}}\n\n[[Category:2019 albums]]\n[[Category:Slipknot (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Roadrunner Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Greg Fidelman]]\n[[Category:Nu metal albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = We Are Not Your Kind\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]\n| cover        = Slipknot - We Are Not Your Kind.png\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{start date|2019|8|9}}\n| recorded     = November 2018 \u2013 April 2019\n| studio       = [[EastWest Studios]]<br />(Hollywood, Los Angeles, California)\n| genre        = * [[Nu metal]]\n* [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]\n* {{nowrap|[[groove metal]]}}\n* [[extreme metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n| length       = 63:29\n| label        = [[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]\n| producer     = * [[Greg Fidelman]]\n* Slipknot\n| prev_title   = [[Day of the Gusano: Live in Mexico]]\n| prev_year    = 2017\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = We Are Not Your Kind\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Unsainted]]\n | single1date = May 16, 2019\n | single2     = [[Solway Firth (song)|Solway Firth]]\n | single2date = July 22, 2019\n | single3 = [[Birth of the Cruel]]\n | single3date = August 5, 2019\n | single4 = [[Nero Forte]]\n | single4date = December 16, 2019\n }}\n}}\n'''''We Are Not Your Kind''''' is the sixth studio album by American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]. Recorded at [[EastWest Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]] with co-producer [[Greg Fidelman]] (who previously produced the band's 2014 album ''[[.5: The Gray Chapter]]''), it was released on August 9, 2019 by [[Roadrunner Records]]. The title is taken from a lyric in the song \"[[All Out Life]]\", which was released as a standalone single in 2018 and features as a bonus track on the Japanese edition of the album. ''We Are Not Your Kind'' is the first Slipknot album to be recorded as an eight-member band, as their former percussionist [[Chris Fehn]] departed the band in March 2019 after suing the group for alleged unpaid royalties. \n\nAfter the conclusion of the touring cycle for ''.5: The Gray Chapter'', Slipknot guitarist [[Jim Root]] and percussionist [[Shawn Crahan|Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan]] began writing and demoing material for the band's follow-up album in early 2017. According to Crahan, the group wrote and recorded a total of 22 songs and 26 interludes, with the plan initially being to produce the band's first [[double album]]. Recording began in November 2018, shortly after the release of the standalone single \"[[All Out Life]]\". The album was completed by April 2019 and \"[[Unsainted]]\" was released as the lead single the next month. This was followed by \"[[Solway Firth (song)|Solway Firth]]\" in July, \"[[Birth of the Cruel]]\" in August and \"[[Nero Forte]]\" in December.\n\n''We Are Not Your Kind'' received critical acclaim; numerous commentators hailed the album as one of the best releases of Slipknot's career, praising the level of experimentation displayed on several key songs. Others highlighted it as a modern landmark release in the heavy metal genre. \"Unsainted\" reached number 10 on the US ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]] chart, while \"Solway Firth\" also reached the [[UK Rock & Metal Singles and Albums Charts|UK Rock & Metal Singles Chart]] top ten. ''We Are Not Your Kind'' debuted at number 1 on both the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and the [[UK Albums Chart]], as well as several other charts around the world.\n\n==Background and writing==\nWork on Slipknot's sixth studio album began in February 2017, when the band's guitarist [[Jim Root]] and percussionist [[Shawn Crahan|Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan]] started writing new material together. Speaking to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in November 2016, Crahan simply stated that \"we want to write\", but that a recording timeline would remain unconfirmed for the time being.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/slipknots-shawn-clown-crahan-on-bloody-directorial-debut-126375/ |title=Slipknot's Shawn 'Clown' Crahan on Bloody Directorial Debut |last=Grow |first=Kory |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=November 22, 2016 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> He later elaborated on this plan by claiming that the group's members wanted to take their time working on new songs, rather than producing it within a set timeframe as they had done before.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metalinsider.net/interviews/shawn-clown-crahan-talks-officer-downe-next-slipknot-album |title=Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan talks 'Officer Downe,' next Slipknot album |last=Teitelman |first=Bram |work=Metal Insider |date=November 23, 2016 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Plans for the direction of the album had been touted by the percussionist as early as the summer of 2015, when he claimed that he wanted to write an \"[[Concept album|art record]]\" in the vein of ''[[The Wall]]'' by [[Pink Floyd]] or ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' by [[the Beatles]], likely in the form of a [[double album]] with an overall concept and numerous [[Instrumental|interlude]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/clown-wants-slipknot-to-make-double-concept-album-weve-gotta-write-our-the-wall-or-sgt-peppers/ |title=Clown Wants Slipknot To Make Double Concept Album: We've Gotta Write Our 'The Wall' Or 'Sgt. Pepper's' |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=June 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Several song ideas also came from rough demos tracked during the previous tour, with Crahan estimating that the band had \"hundreds of ideas\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/slipknot-has-hundreds-of-ideas-for-next-album-says-shawn-clown-crahan/ |title=Slipknot Has 'Hundreds Of Ideas' For Next Album, Says Shawn 'Clown' Crahan |website=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=March 6, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nBy August 2017, Crahan estimated that the writing process had spawned \"about 27 pieces of work\" so far. In an interview with the ''[[NME]]'', he added that \"A lot of us are meeting up in September to start working on those 27 pieces of music and we're going to add to that,\" reasserting his desire to make a double album.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/slipknot-new-album-tour-2017-2018-interview-clown-2121111 |title=What's next for Slipknot? |last=Trendell |first=Andrew |work=[[NME]] |date=August 4, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Following up with ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' in October, Crahan revealed that he had been working with Root and drummer [[Jay Weinberg]] on organizing the material written during the previous touring cycle, which combined with new material resulted in \"seven or eight\" full song ideas.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/slipknots-clown-we-have-eight-new-songs |title=Slipknot's Clown: \"We have eight new songs\" |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=October 31, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Much of the initial writing process took place without the band's frontman [[Corey Taylor]], who spent 2017 recording and touring in promotion of ''[[Hydrograd]]'', the sixth album by his other band [[Stone Sour]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/slipknot_new_music_corey_taylor/ |title=Corey Taylor \"hasn't even heard\" any of Slipknot's new music |work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The vocalist began writing lyrics for three new songs in early 2018, which he claimed would be based on events in his life over the last few years.<ref name=\"autobiographical\">{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/corey-taylor-says-new-slipknot-music-is-awesome-promises-most-autobiographical-lyrics-in-years/ |title=Corey Taylor Says New Slipknot Music Is 'Awesome,' Promises 'Most Autobiographical' Lyrics In Years |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=February 14, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> By April, Taylor claimed that he had completed lyrics for \"almost all\" of the band's new music.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8288889/stone-sour-st-marie-video |title=Stone Sour Unveils 'St. Marie' Video, Indulging In 'Country Side' of Band: Premiere |last=Graff |first=Gary |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=April 5, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n{{multiple image|caption_align=left|header_align=center\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 218\n| image1 = Slipknot - The Grey Chapter Tour 2016 - D\u00fcsseldorf - 01948151 - Leonhard Kreissig - Canon EOS 5D Mark II.jpg\n| image2 = Slipknot - The Grey Chapter Tour 2016 - D\u00fcsseldorf - 02010705 - Leonhard Kreissig - Canon EOS 5D Mark III.jpg\n| footer = Writing for ''We Are Not Your Kind'' was initially spearheaded by [[Shawn Crahan|Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan]] (top) and [[Jim Root]] (bottom).\n}}\nAfter almost two years of writing, [[Shawn Crahan]] revealed that recording for Slipknot's sixth album would begin in November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/slipknots-clown-on-knotfest-the-end-of-the-band-and-his-relationship-with-joey-jordison-2171696 |title=Slipknot's Clown on Knotfest, the end of the band, and his relationship with Joey Jordison |last=de Gallier |first=Thea |work=[[NME]] |date=December 18, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The full band later joined the percussionist in January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/slipknot-record-new-album-january/ |title=Confirmed: Slipknot to Record New Album in January |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=November 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Production was handled again by [[Greg Fidelman]], who engineered and mixed 2004's ''[[Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)]]'', and produced 2014's ''[[.5: The Gray Chapter]]'' and the 2018 single \"[[All Out Life]]\". Speaking about working with the producer, vocalist [[Corey Taylor]] credited Fidelman with his contributions to their previous releases and noted that \"He gets us, he challenges us ... we have a great relationship with him\".<ref name=\"fidelman\">{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/slipknots-corey-taylor-praises-producer-greg-fidelman-bashes-rick-rubin-ahead-of-new-album-recording-sessions/ |title=Slipknot's Corey Taylor Praises Producer Greg Fidelman, Bashes Rick Rubin Ahead Of New Album Recording Sessions |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=January 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> It was initially suggested in the media that [[Ross Robinson]], who worked with the band on 1999's ''[[Slipknot (album)|Slipknot]]'' and 2001's ''[[Iowa (album)|Iowa]]'', would be producing the album, however this rumor was quickly dismissed by guitarist [[Jim Root]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/slipknot-ross-robinson-not-producing-new-album/ |title=Slipknot guitarist says 'Iowa' producer not involved with new album |last=Casteel |first=Beth |work=[[Alternative Press (magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=October 1, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The recording of ''We Are Not Your Kind'' was completed by April 2019, when turntablist and keyboardist [[Sid Wilson]] revealed that he was \"laying the last\" of his parts on the album.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/slipknots-sid-wilson-is-laying-the-last-of-his-parts-down-for-new-album/ |title=Slipknot's Sid Wilson Is 'Laying The Last' Of His Parts Down For New Album |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nSpeaking to British retailer [[HMV]] about the album's recording process, Root recalled that the band spent a lot of time working on initial arrangements for the new material, explaining that \"We spent all the time on the demos. We built them and let them evolve.\"<ref name=\"hmv\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hmv.com/music/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-interview |title=Slipknot We Are Not Your Kind interview |author=Tom |website=[[HMV]] |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> This allowed the band to \"step back\" from recordings and revisit them later, leading to what the guitarist described as an \"organic\" outcome.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rocksound.tv/features/read/jim-root-on-slipknots-tortilla-man-im-surprised-that-nobody-has-sussed-out |title=Jim Root On Slipknot's 'Tortilla Man': \"I'm Surprised That Nobody Has Sussed Out Who It Is Yet\" |last=Sayce |first=Rob |work=[[Rock Sound]] |date=August 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> However, he added that the final tracking process was \"a big challenge\", lamenting that \"I wish we'd had that time to actually record the album.\"<ref name=\"hmv\"/> Root also distinguished the approach on ''We Are Not Your Kind'' from its predecessor ''.5: The Gray Chapter''; he recalled that for the 2014 release \"[The] songs came straight from my garage and they don't have the push and pull of a live band,\" contrasting the recording of its follow-up by explaining that \"we were playing the songs as a band and tracked them with and without a [[click track]]. The ones without click are the ones that we used on the record.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/jim-root-corey-and-i-would-have-killed-each-other-if-i-stayed-in-stone-sour |title=Jim Root: Corey and I would have killed each other if I stayed in Stone Sour |last=Munro |first=Scott |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=August 6, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nDue to the amount of time spent writing and recording demos for the album, there are many tracks from the ''We Are Not Your Kind'' sessions which remain unreleased. According to Crahan, the band recorded a total of 22 songs and 26 interludes for the album, with many shelved in favor of stronger tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/08/slipknot-shawn-clown-crahan-interview-2019/ |title=Slipknot's Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan on We Are Not Your Kind, Mastering One's Craft, and Finding One's Self |last=Pementel |first=Michael |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=August 13, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Before the album's release, the percussionist revealed to ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine that \"There's another 15 songs that didn't make the cut\", estimating that \"there's at least seven or eight songs that are recorded, with vocals, that did not make this album.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/slipknot-have-another-15-songs-that-didnt-make-the-cut-for-we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=Slipknot Have Another \"15 Songs\" That Didn't Make The Cut For We Are Not Your Kind |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=July 30, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Speaking on music streaming service [[Spotify]]'s ''Metal Talks'' podcast, Crahan explained that when choosing what songs to include on an album, he tries to \"picture [himself] as a fan in the world that we live in today\".<ref name=\"spotify\">{{cite news |url=https://www.rawmusictv.com/article/amp/2019/Clown-explains-why-All-Out-Life-was-left-off-We-Are-Not-Your-Kind |title=Clown explains why All Out Life was left off We Are Not Your Kind |last=Speed |first=AC |work=RawMusicTV |date=August 12, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> He went on to say that this line of thinking is what ultimately led to the exclusion of \"[[All Out Life]]\" from the album, claiming that he believed fans would prefer to hear a new song in place of one that was already available to stream.<ref name=\"spotify\"/>\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\nMusically, ''We Are Not Your Kind'' has been described as [[nu metal]],<ref name=\"rolling stone\">{{cite web |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=Slipknot Get Even Creepier Than Usual on \u2018We Are Not Your Kind\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-review-867704/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=August 9, 2019 |date=August 9, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"metal injection 2\">{{cite web|last1=Cordova|first1=Daniel|title=The Weekly Injection: New Releases From Slipknot, The Contortionist, and More Out Today \u2013 8/9 |url=https://metalinjection.net/upcoming-releases/heavy-new-releases/new-releases-from-slipknot-the-contortionist-and-more-out-today-8-9|website=Metal Injection|accessdate=August 9, 2019|date=August 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]],<ref name=\"sonicperspectives\">{{cite web|last1=Lester|first1=Jordan|title=Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind (Album Review)|url=https://www.sonicperspectives.com/album-reviews/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind/|accessdate=August 11, 2019|date=August 8, 2019}}</ref> [[groove metal]],<ref name=\"metal injection 2\"/> [[extreme metal]]<ref name=\"nme\" /> and [[hard rock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8527688/slipknot-third-no-1-album-billboard-200|title=Slipknot Ties Up Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'We Are Not Your Kind'|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=August 18, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> ''We Are Not Your Kind'' has been recognized by commentators and band members as one of the most experimental albums of Slipknot's career. The album  features moody instrumentals and [[Electronic music|electronic]] elements.<ref name=\"rolling stone\"/><ref name=\"Sputnikmusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/79986/Slipknot-We-Are-Not-Your-Kind/|title=Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind|work=[[Sputnikmusic]]|date=August 9, 2019|accessdate=August 9, 2019}}</ref> During a pre-release interview with [[Daniel P. Carter]] on the [[BBC Radio 1]] Rock Show, [[Corey Taylor]] claimed that \"it is probably the furthest we've pushed the boundaries of creativity and experimentation,\" adding that \"We not only went places that we've hinted at musically over the years, but never really went full-board, but we're also doing heavier things than we've ever done.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/corey-taylor-on-we-are-not-your-kind-this-is-probably-the-furthest-weve-pushed-the-boundaries-of-creativity/ |title=Corey Taylor On We Are Not Your Kind: \"This Is Probably The Furthest We've Pushed The Boundaries Of Creativity\" |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=June 24, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Emily Carter of ''[[Kerrang!]]'' described it as \"the 'Knot's most experimental album to date,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/slipknot-jim-roots-track-by-track-guide-to-we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=Slipknot: Jim Root's Track By Track Guide To We Are Not Your Kind |last=Carter |first=Emily |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' writer Jordan Bassett called it \"Slipknot at their artiest\",<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-review |title=Slipknot \u2013 'We Are Not Your Kind' review |last=Bassett |first=Jordan |work=[[NME]] |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> and Roisin O'Connor of ''[[The Independent]]'' claimed that \"The sheer ambition of ''We Are Not Your Kind'' is just as staggering as their seminal record ''[[Iowa (album)|Iowa]]''\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/slipknot-review-we-are-not-your-kind-album-stream-tracklist-corey-taylor-clown-masks-a9045511.html |title=Slipknot review, We Are Not Your Kind: The rage they capture is universally felt |last=O'Connor |first=Roisin |work=[[The Independent]] |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Several critics highlighted \"Spiders\" as one of the most [[Avant-garde music|avant-garde]] songs on the album, on which \"creepy piano tinklings\" and \"scattershot drum beats\" are favored over the more common low-end guitar riffs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/slipknots-we-are-not-your-kind-your-ultimate-track-by-track-guide |title=Slipknot's We Are Not Your Kind: Your ultimate track-by-track guide |last1=Alderslade |first1=Merlin |last2=Goodman |first2=Eleanor |last3=Edwards |first3=Briony |last4=Pattillo |first4=Alice |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/corey-taylor-slipknot-david-bowie-black-metal-song-interview/ |title=Corey Taylor: One New Slipknot Song Is Like Black Metal David Bowie |last=DiVita |first=Joe |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/09/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-review |title=Slipknot: We Are Not Your Kind review \u2013 Iowan behemoths' most brutal, gentle album |last=Simpson |first=Dave |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAnother quality of ''We Are Not Your Kind'' touted in the build-up to its release was the heaviness of the music. As early as June 2018, Taylor claimed that their sixth album would be \"''Iowa'' levels of heavy\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/corey-taylor-the-new-slipknot-album-is-iowa-levels-of-heavy/ |title=Corey Taylor: The New Slipknot Album Is \"Iowa Levels Of Heavy\" |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=June 21, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> He later reiterated the suggestion, claiming that the album contains one of the heaviest songs of their career.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/slipknot-weve-just-written-one-of-the-heaviest-songs-of-our-career |title=Slipknot: We've just written one of the heaviest songs of our career |last=Munro |first=Scott |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=October 18, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Sam Taylor of the ''[[Financial Times]]'' admitted that the band \"weren't bluffing\" when making such claims, suggesting that the album \"often verges on the attritional\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/55391dbc-b83f-11e9-8a88-aa6628ac896c |title=Slipknot: We Are Not Your Kind \u2014 some of their heaviest music yet |last=Taylor |first=Sam |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Similarly, ''[[Gigwise]]'' writer Anna Smith suggested that ''We Are Not Your Kind'' featured \"some of the heaviest material since [the band's] [[Slipknot (album)|eponymous debut]]\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gigwise.com/reviews/3350129/album-review-slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind |title=Album Review: Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind |last=Smith |first=Anna |work=[[Gigwise]] |date=August 6, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Reviewing the album for the website [[Blabbermouth.net]], Jay H. Gorania praised the band's attempts at being heavy on ''We Are Not Your Kind'' \u2013 describing their first two albums, Gorania opined that \"Slipknot seemed as though they were trying to be the heaviest band on the market and trying too hard,\" before concluding that \"When they are in overdrive nowadays, however, it feels more authentic and expressive.\"<ref name=\"blabbermouth\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=CD Reviews \u2013 Slipknot: \"We Are Not Your Kind\" |last=Gorania |first=Jay H. |website=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Taylor, ''We Are Not Your Kind'' features some of his most personal lyrics to date. During the writing process, the band's frontman explained that \"It's been a heavy couple of years for me personally. [...] I've been able to kind of grab hold of some of the depression that I've been fighting and kind of formulate the way that I want to describe it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/corey-taylor-new-slipknot-lyrics-most-shared-years/ |title=Corey Taylor: New Slipknot Lyrics Are 'Most I've Shared' in Years |last=Kajzer |first=Jackie |author-link=Full Metal Jackie |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=June 5, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Early on in the process, he claimed that \"It's probably the most autobiographical I've been in years\", describing the lyrical content as \"dark ... really dark\".<ref name=\"autobiographical\"/> One of the main influences on Taylor's lyrics was his separation from then-wife Stephanie Luby in 2016; in an interview with ''[[Loudwire]]'', he explained that \"The narrative [of the album] really came from me working my way through the repercussions of a really toxic relationship. And the fallout that came with finally extricating myself from that relationship.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/slipknot-corey-taylor-interview-2019-embrace-pain-art/ |title=Interview: Corey Taylor Once Again Embraced Pain to Create Art |last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=August 8, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Another major influence on the album's lyrical content is that of global \"divisiveness\",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/corey-taylor-slipknot-tour-pass-torch-interview/ |title=Corey Taylor: Slipknot's Diverse Tour Lineup Helps Pass the Torch |last=Kajzer |first=Jackie |author-link=Full Metal Jackie |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=July 29, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> which Taylor claims is fueled by US President [[Donald Trump]] through \"bigotry\" and \"racism\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.avclub.com/slipknot-singer-writes-book-about-how-trump-s-election-1798262848 |title=Slipknot singer writes book about how Trump's election is a \"fucking nightmare\" |last=McLevy |first=Alex |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=June 12, 2017 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Promotion and release==\n{{Main|We Are Not Your Kind World Tour}}\n[[File:Slipknot - The Grey Chapter Tour 2016 - D\u00fcsseldorf - 00568151 - Leonhard Kreissig - Canon EOS 5D Mark II.jpg|thumb|left|Percussionist [[Chris Fehn]] was fired from Slipknot in March 2019, after suing the band claiming unpaid royalties.]]\nThe first new song released during the recording process for ''We Are Not Your Kind'' was the single \"[[All Out Life]]\" on October 31, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/slipknot-new-song-video-all-out-life-750064/ |title=Hear Slipknot's Brutal New Song 'All Out Life' |last=Reed |first=Ryan |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=October 31, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> It was produced by [[Greg Fidelman]], who later also worked on the album.<ref name=\"fidelman\"/> The song's [[music video]], directed by [[Shawn Crahan|Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://planetradio.co.uk/kerrang/entertainment/music/slipknot-all-out-life/ |title=Slipknot unleash new single 'All Out Life' and M. Shawn Crahan directed video |last=Colothan |first=Scott |work=[[Kerrang Radio]] |date=October 31, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> broke the band's record for most views in a single day on [[YouTube]], with more than 3.4 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/slipknots-all-out-life-breaks-youtube-record |title=Slipknot's All Out Life breaks YouTube record |last=Munro |first=Scott |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=November 8, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The track was initially slated to appear on ''We Are Not Your Kind'' (the title of which is lifted from one of the song's main lyrics), however when the track listing was revealed it was not included; vocalist [[Corey Taylor]] later explained that \"it was kind of its own thing that really just let people know that we weren't gone\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/corey-taylor-explains-why-all-out-life-isnt-on-the-new-slipknot-album/ |title=Corey Taylor Explains Why All Out Life Isn't On The New Slipknot Album |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=May 28, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> In February 2019, the band launched a teaser website at the URL wearenotyourkind.com,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/slipknot-launch-new-website-wearenotyourkind-com/ |title=Slipknot Launch New Website, WeAreNotYourKind.com |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=February 28, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> with the album's release date confirmed a few days later.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/slipknot-announce-the-knotfest-roadshow-and-reveal-new-album-release-date |title=Slipknot announce the Knotfest Roadshow \u2013 and reveal new album release date |last=Munro |first=Scott |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=March 4, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Two months later, the band revealed the track listing for the album and officially confirmed that it would be called ''We Are Not Your Kind''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/slipknot-unveil-new-masks-video-sainted-along-details-new-album-not-kind-2488714 |title=Slipknot reveal new album title, video, and masks |last=Trendell |first=Andrew |work=[[NME]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nLess than two weeks after the announcement of the album's release date, it was revealed that percussionist [[Chris Fehn]] was suing the rest of the band (with Taylor and Crahan named as separate defendants), claiming that royalties from merchandising and touring had been withheld from him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theblast.com/c/slipknot-metal-band-chris-fehn-drummer-lawsuit |title=Slipknot Drummer Chris Fehn Sues Band Over Money Dispute |work=The Blast |date=March 14, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> A few days later he was dismissed from the band, with the official news release stating that \"Chris knows why he is no longer a part of Slipknot. We are disappointed that he chose to point fingers and manufacture claims, rather than doing what was necessary to continue to be a part of Slipknot.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/03/slipknot-part-ways-chris-fehn/ |title=Slipknot part ways with percussionist Chris Fehn |last=Kaufman |first=Spencer |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=March 18, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Fehn's position was taken by an as-yet unknown replacement, dubbed by fans as \"Tortilla Man\" due to the design of his mask.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/former-slipknot-percussionist-chris-fehn-fights-continue-lawsuit-band-profits-2527450 |title=Former Slipknot percussionist Chris Fehn fights to continue lawsuit over band profits |last=Richards |first=Will |work=[[NME]] |date=July 11, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> [[Jim Root]] later claimed that Fehn's departure had little impact on the production of the album.<ref name=\"hmv\"/>\n\nOn May 16, 2019, the day of the album's official announcement, Slipknot released \"[[Unsainted]]\" as the first single from ''We Are Not Your Kind'', alongside a music video which revealed each member's new mask.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/watch-slipknot-finally-reveal-new-masks-in-video-for-unsainted-single |title=Watch Slipknot finally reveal new masks in video for Unsainted single |last=Pattillo |first=Alice |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The video broke the record set by \"All Out Life\" as the band's most popular in its first 24 hours on YouTube, receiving over 4.7 million views.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/slipknot-unsainted-personal-record/ |title=Slipknot Break Personal Record With 'Unsainted' |last=Trapp |first=Philip |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=May 23, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The single peaked at number 10 on the US ''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Mainstream Rock]] chart, the band's highest position since \"[[The Devil in I]]\" in 2014,<ref name=\"USmain\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/slipknot/chart-history/hot-mainstream-rock-tracks |title=Slipknot Chart History: Mainstream Rock Songs |work=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]] |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> and at number 68 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], the band's highest position since \"[[Psychosocial (song)|Psychosocial]]\" in 2008.<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/7945/slipknot/ |title=Slipknot Full Official Chart History |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Both \"Unsainted\" and \"All Out Life\" received their live premieres the following day, when the band performed on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' in their first live appearance since November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/slipknot-unsainted-all-out-life-kimmel-837108/ |title=See Slipknot's Live Debut of 'Unsainted,' 'All Out Life' on 'Kimmel' |last=Kreps |first=Daniel |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 18, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> \"[[Solway Firth (song)|Solway Firth]]\" was released as the album's second single on July 22,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/slipknots-solway-firth-the-first-reaction |title=The first reaction to Slipknot's new single Solway Firth |last=Rees |first=Adam |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> reaching number 14 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Rock Songs chart.<ref name=\"USrock\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/slipknot/chart-history/rock-songs |title=Slipknot Chart History: Hot Rock Songs |work=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]] |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> On August 5, \"Birth of the Cruel\", was released as the third single and \"Nero Forte\" was the fourth single, released on December 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/08/slipknot-birth-of-the-cruel/|title=Slipknot \u2014 \"Birth of the Cruel\"|last=Serota |first=Maggie |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=August 5, 2019 |accessdate=August 25, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing their brief performance on ''Jimmy Kimmel Live!'', Slipknot performed at a number of European festivals during the summer of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/slipknot-announces-summer-2019-european-tour/ |title=Slipknot Announces Summer 2019 European Tour |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=October 23, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The run included the band's fourth headline slot at the UK's [[Download Festival]] in June,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/slipknot-download-headline-review/ |title=Reviewed: Every Slipknot Download Headline Performance |last=Ruskell |first=Nick |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=October 23, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> footage from which was later included in the \"Solway Firth\" music video.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/slipknot-unveil-new-track-solway-firth-2531392 |title=Slipknot return with furious new track 'Solway Firth' \u2013 listen |last=Reilly |first=Nick |work=[[NME]] |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> This was followed by the first [[Knotfest|Knotfest Roadshow]] tour in North America from July to September.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/slipknot-announces-knotfest-roadshow-tour-with-volbeat-gojira-and-behemoth/ |title=Slipknot Announces Knotfest Roadshow Tour With Volbeat, Gojira And Behemoth |website=Blabbermouth.net |date=March 4, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> Slipknot was due to open for [[Metallica]] later in the year for a run of shows in Australia and New Zealand on its [[WorldWired Tour]], however the shows were later cancelled due to Metallica frontman [[James Hetfield]] entering rehab.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://loudwire.com/metallica-slipknot-2019-tour/ |title=Metallica Announce 2019 Australian Tour With Slipknot |last=Schaffner |first=Lauryn |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=March 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> A tour of the UK and Europe will follow in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/slipknot-announce-2020-uk-and-european-tour |title=Slipknot announce 2020 UK and European tour |last=Munro |first=Scott |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> ''We Are Not Your Kind'' was released worldwide on August 9, 2019 by [[Roadrunner Records]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/slipknots-we-are-not-your-kind-a-timeline/ |title=Slipknot's We Are Not Your Kind: The Definitive Timeline |last=Krovatin |first=Chris |work=[[Kerrang!]] |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> \"All Out Life\" was featured as a [[Album#Bonus tracks|bonus track]] on the Japanese edition of the release.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.spin.com/2019/08/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-stream/ |title=Stream Slipknot's New Album We Are Not Your Kind |last=Arcand |first=Rob |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 7.8/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|url=http://anydecentmusic.com/review/10014/Slipknot-We-Are-Not-Your-Kind.aspx|title=We Are Not Your Kind by Slipknot reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 89/100<ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/we-are-not-your-kind/slipknot |title=We Are Not Your Kind by Slipknot Reviews and Tracks |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/we-are-not-your-kind-mw0003283853 |title=We Are Not Your Kind \u2013 Slipknot: Songs, Reviews, Credits |last=Monger |first=James Christopher |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A<ref name=\"consequence\">{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/08/album-review-slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind |last=Pementel |first=Michael |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=August 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev3score = 8/10<ref name=\"exclaim\">{{cite web |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/slipknot-we_are_not_your_kind |title=Slipknot: We Are Not Your Kind |last=Smith-Engelhardt |first=Joe |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"independent\"/>\n| rev6 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"kerrang\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=Album Review: Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind |last=Carter |first=Emily |work=[[Kerrang!]] |date=August 7, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Metal Hammer]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"hammer\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loudersound.com/reviews/slipknot-are-back-and-as-bold-as-ever-in-we-are-not-your-kind |title=Review: Slipknot's We Are Not Your Kind album |last=Rees |first=Adam |work=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=August 1, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"nme\"/>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 6.7/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind/ |title=Slipknot: We Are Not Your Kind Album Review |last=O'Connor |first=Andy |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=August 14, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"rollingstone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-review-867704/ |title=Review: Slipknot's New Album 'We Are Not Your Kind' |last=Grow |first=Kory |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''We Are Not Your Kind'' was met with critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average]] score of 89, based on 14 reviews.<ref name=\"metacritic\"/> ''[[Forbes]]'' writer Quentin Singer claimed that the album was \"a metal [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/quentinsinger/2019/08/11/review-the-rumors-are-true-slipknot-have-delivered-a-metal-magnum-opus/ |title=Review: The Rumors Are True, Slipknot Have Delivered A Metal Magnum Opus |last=Singer |first=Quentin |work=[[Forbes]] |date=August 11, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn a five-star review for the ''[[NME]]'', Jordan Bassett described ''We Are Not Your Kind'' as \"an astonishing record: a roaring, horrifying delve into the guts of the band's revulsion, a primal scream of endlessly inventive extreme metal and searing misanthropy\".<ref name=\"nme\"/> ''[[Kerrang!]]'' writer Emily Carter also gave the album a perfect rating, writing that \"20 years since their debut, Slipknot are as bold, fearless and exhilarating as ever.\"<ref name=\"kerrang\"/> Roisin O'Connor of ''[[The Independent]]'' gushed that \"The sheer ambition of ''We Are Not Your Kind'' is just as staggering as their seminal record ''[[Iowa (album)|Iowa]]'' [and] the dynamic might be even better\".<ref name=\"independent\"/> Similarly, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' writer Michael Pementel hailed the album as a strong evolution of the band's style, dubbing it \"one of the strongest albums in their career\".<ref name=\"consequence\"/> Joe Smith-Engelhardt of ''[[Exclaim!]]'' described it as \"a return to form\" following their last two albums, which he called \"a tad formulaic\".<ref name=\"exclaim\"/> [[Blabbermouth.net]]'s Jay H. Gorania called it \"a shining gem in Slipknot's crown\".<ref name=\"blabbermouth\"/>\n\nMultiple critics hailed lead single \"Unsainted\" as one of the album's highlights. Bassett called the song \"one of the greatest things Slipknot have ever done\",<ref name=\"nme\"/> while Kory Grow of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' described it as \"one of the catchiest \u2013 and grittiest \u2013 songs of the band's career\".<ref name=\"rollingstone\"/> Anna Smith of ''[[Gigwise]]'' called the song \"a welcome amalgamation of old and new\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> Other commentators focused on the level of experimentation present on the album. Adam Rees of ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' highlighted \"A Liar's Funeral\" and \"Not Long for This World\" as having \"the biggest impact\" on the album,<ref name=\"hammer\"/> while ''[[Loudwire]]'' contributor Jon Wiederhorn wrote that \"With ''We Are Not Your Kind'' ... Slipknot have done more than play to their strengths, they've broadly expanded their parameters, taking the band in musical directions that they've previously only hinted at.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://loudwire.com/slipknot-we-are-not-your-kind-album-review-2019/ |title=Review: Slipknot's 'We Are Not Your Kind' Full of Experimentation |last=Wiederhorn |first=Jon |work=[[Loudwire]] |date=August 5, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref> The band's frontman [[Corey Taylor]] also received widespread praise for his lyrics and vocals, described by Carter as \"outstanding\"<ref name=\"kerrang\"/> and by Pementel as \"remarkable\".<ref name=\"consequence\"/>\n\nVery few reviews of ''We Are Not Your Kind'' featured major criticisms for the album. Pementel admitted that \"To be frank, given all the stylization, the production, and creativity taking place, it's tough to find something wrong with the album,\" claiming that \"fans who pine for the band's early sound may not latch onto ''We Are Not Your Kind'' immediately \u2013 but even those listeners will likely come around to this exceptional LP.\"<ref name=\"consequence\"/> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' contributor Andy O'Connor admitted that while the album \"has more to offer than expected\", it is \"still sometimes frustratingly short-sighted\", claiming that \"Slipknot know what works for them and they exploit it to a fault\".<ref name=\"pitchfork\"/> While hailing the release as \"easily the best album Slipknot has produced in 15 years\", [[Sputnikmusic]] complained of the album's length and its \"homogenised stomping rhythm\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/79986/Slipknot-We-Are-Not-Your-Kind/ |title=Review: Slipknot \u2013 We Are Not Your Kind |author=Simon |website=[[Sputnikmusic]] |date=August 9, 2019 |accessdate=August 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''We Are Not Your Kind'' opened at the top ten in more than 20 album charts, debuting atop about 10 (including Australian, Belgian, Canadian, Finnish, Irish, Portuguese, Spanish, British and American charts). The album debuted atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 118,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s including 102,000 pure album sales, becoming Slipknot's third album to reach the country's summit after ''[[All Hope Is Gone]]'' and ''[[.5: The Gray Chapter]]''.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8527688/slipknot-third-no-1-album-billboard-200|title=Slipknot Ties Up Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'We Are Not Your Kind'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=August 18, 2019|accessdate=August 19, 2019}}</ref> Ten previously uncharted album tracks also registered on the ''Billboard'' Hot Rock Songs chart \u2013 \"Nero Forte\" at number 11, \"Birth of the Cruel\" at number 14, \"Critical Darling\" at number 19, \"Orphan\" at number 28, \"Red Flag\" at number 30, \"Spiders\" at number 34, \"A Liar's Funeral\" at number 38, \"Insert Coin\" at number 39, \"Death Because of Death\" at number 40 and \"Not Long for This World\" at number 43.<ref name=\"USrock\"/> The album debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], giving the band its first UK number one since 2001's ''[[Iowa (album)|Iowa]]''.<ref name=\"OCC\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Shawn Crahan, Jim Root and Corey Taylor<ref>{{cite web |last1=ASCAP |title=ACE Repertory |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/performer/SLIPKNOT |website=ASCAP |accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n| title1 = Insert Coin\n| length1 = 1:38\n| title2 = [[Unsainted]]\n| length2 = 4:20\n| title3 = [[Birth of the Cruel]]\n| length3 = 4:35\n| title4 = Death Because of Death\n| length4 = 1:20\n| title5 = [[Nero Forte]]\n| length5 = 5:15\n| title6 = Critical Darling\n| length6 = 6:25\n| title7 = A Liar's Funeral\n| length7 = 5:27\n| title8 = Red Flag\n| length8 = 4:11\n| title9 = What's Next\n| length9 = 0:53\n| title10 = Spiders\n| length10 = 4:03\n| title11 = Orphan\n| length11 = 6:01\n| title12 = My Pain\n| length12 = 6:48\n| title13 = Not Long for This World\n| length13 = 6:35\n| title14 = [[Solway Firth (song)|Solway Firth]]\n| length14 = 5:56\n| total_length = 63:27\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Japanese edition bonus track\n| collapsed = yes\n| title15 = [[All Out Life]]\n| length15 = 5:40\n| total_length = 69:07\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from album's [[liner notes]].<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title= We Are Not Your Kind |year= 2019 |type= booklet |publisher=[[Roadrunner Records|Roadrunner]]}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n'''Slipknot'''\n*(#8) [[Corey Taylor]] \u2013 lead and backing vocals, production\n*(#7) [[Mick Thomson]] \u2013 guitars, production\n*(#4) [[Jim Root]] \u2013 guitars, production\n*(#6) [[Shawn Crahan|Shawn \"Clown\" Crahan]] \u2013 custom percussion, backing vocals, production, art direction, photography\n*(#0) [[Sid Wilson]] \u2013 turntables, keyboards, production\n*(#5) [[Craig Jones (musician)|Craig \"133\" Jones]] \u2013 samples, media, keyboards, production\n*[[Alessandro Venturella]] \u2013 bass, piano, synthesiser<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/slipknots-vman-my-approach-isnt-the-same-as-pauls-i-cant-be-him-and-never-will-be|title=Slipknot's VMan: \u201cMy approach isn\u2019t the same as Paul\u2019s. I can\u2019t be him and never will be\u201d|first=Amit|last=Sharma2019-10-16T09:41:54Z|website=MusicRadar}}</ref>, production\n*[[Jay Weinberg]] \u2013 drums, production\n'''Additional musicians'''\n*[[Angel City Chorale]] \u2013 choral vocals on \"[[Unsainted]]\"\n*Kat Primetau \u2013 additional vocals on \"Death Because of Death\"\n*[[Chris Fehn]] \u2013 percussion and backing vocals on \"[[All Out Life]]\"\n{{col-2-of-2}}\n'''Additional personnel'''\n*[[Greg Fidelman]] \u2013 production, engineering\n*Greg Gordon \u2013 engineering\n*Sara Killion \u2013 engineering\n*Paul Fig \u2013 engineering\n*Bo Bodnar \u2013 engineering assistance\n*Chaz Sexton \u2013 engineering assistance\n*[[Joe Barresi]] \u2013 mixing\n*Jun Murakawa \u2013 mixing assistance\n*[[Dan Monti]] \u2013 editing\n*[[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013 mastering\n*Michael Boland \u2013 design\n*Alexandria Crahan-Conway \u2013 band photography\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|1|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Austria|3|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Flanders|1|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Wallonia|1|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|1|artist=Slipknot|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Czech|4|date=201933|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 20, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Denmark|7|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 21, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Netherlands|2|artist=Slipknot|album=We Are Not Your Kind|r